Part One - Project based¶

CONTEXT: Medical research university X is undergoing a deep research on patients with certain conditions. University has an internal AI team. Due to confidentiality the patient’s details and the conditions are masked by the client by providing different datasets to the AI team for developing a AIML model which can predict the condition of the patient depending on the received test results.

In [31]:
def calculateLowerAndUpperFence(col_name,df):
    Q1 = np.percentile(a=df[col_name],q=25) # 25th percentile
    Q3 = np.percentile(a=df[col_name],q=75) # 75th percentile
    IQR = Q3 - Q1 # inter-quartile-range
    cut_off = 1.5 * IQR
    # limit for outliers
    lower_fence = Q1 - cut_off
    upper_fence = Q3 + cut_off
    return lower_fence,upper_fence
In [32]:
def number_of_outliers(col_name,lower_fence,upper_fence,df):
    outliers = np.where((df[col_name] < lower_fence) | (df[col_name] > upper_fence))
    number_of_outliers = len(outliers[0])
    return number_of_outliers
In [33]:
def plotHistogramAndBoxPlotWithOutliers(col_name,df):
    # initialising subplots
    figure, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2)

    # setting figure parameters
    figure.set_figheight(5)
    figure.set_figwidth(15)

    #setting axes titles
    ax[0].set_title(f'Distribution plot of {col_name}')
    ax[1].set_title(f'Box plot of {col_name}')

    # plotting the distribution
    sns.histplot(data=df[col_name],ax=ax[0],kde=True,color='g')
    sns.boxplot(x=df[col_name],ax=ax[1])

    plt.show()

    # figuring upper and lower limits
    lower_fence,upper_fence = calculateLowerAndUpperFence(col_name,df)

    # logical selection of outliers
    no_of_outliers = number_of_outliers(col_name,lower_fence,upper_fence,df)
    print(f'The number of outliers for {col_name} are {no_of_outliers}')
    if no_of_outliers > 0:
        outlier_columns.append(col_name) # capturing an outlier column
        print('The distribution is skewed.')
    print('*****************************************************************')
    # NOTE:: We could also store object of boxplot and figure outliers from `caps`

Data pre-processing¶

  • Imputing values in outlier_columns by bringing values lower than lower_fence upto lower_fence and values higher than upper_fence upto upper_fence.
  • I chose this approach of correcting outliers rather than imputimg to mean, median or zero, because those would change concentration of data and also outliers are more similar to the boundary elements.
In [38]:
def pull_outliers_to_quartile_limits(df):
    for col_name in outlier_columns:
        lower_fence,upper_fence = calculateLowerAndUpperFence(col_name,df)
        print(f'The number of outliers for {col_name} before imputing are {number_of_outliers(col_name,lower_fence,upper_fence,df)}')

        col_index = df.columns.get_loc(col_name)
        # imputing values lower than lower fence equal to lower fence
        for row_index in np.where(df[col_name] < lower_fence)[0]:
            df.iloc[[row_index],[col_index]] = lower_fence

        # imputing values higher than upper fence equal to upper fence
        for row_index in np.where(df[col_name] > upper_fence)[0]:
            df.iloc[[row_index],[col_index]] = upper_fence

        print(f'The number of outliers for {col_name} after imputing are {number_of_outliers(col_name,lower_fence,upper_fence,df)}')
        print()

def visualize_imbalance_in_target_variable(target_variable,col_name):
    # initialising subplots
    figure, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2)

    # setting figure parameters
    figure.set_figheight(5)
    figure.set_figwidth(15)
    
    #setting axes titles
    ax[0].set_title(f'Pie Chart of {col_name}')
    ax[1].set_title(f'Count plot of {col_name}')

    # plotting the distribution
    target_variable.value_counts().plot.pie(ax=ax[0],autopct='%1.1f%%')
    sns.countplot(x=target_variable,ax=ax[1])

    plt.show()

Observations:¶

  • From seeing number of records of each target variable, we can observe that that target variable/class is not balanced.
  • Thus, accuracy score would not be a good metric for performance of the model.
  • The context of the problem is medical field, so recall or true positive rate or specificity or even a balance of precision and recall in F1 score should be considered, because classifying a diseased person as healthy(False Negative) can be very lethal.

def plot_confusion_matrix(y_test,y_pred,lab,actual_labels,pred_labels): # function to plot confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test,y_pred,labels=lab) # getting the confusion matrix
    cm_df = pd.DataFrame(cm, index=[i for i in actual_labels],columns=[i for i in pred_labels])

    plt.figure(figsize=(7,5))

    sns.heatmap(cm_df, annot=True,fmt='g')
    plt.show()

Automating the task of finding the optimal K¶

The misclassifcation rate for that K should be low or the accuracy should be high.

In [63]:
# taking odd number of neigbors
neighbors = np.arange(1,20,2)
In [64]:
accuracy_scores = [] # initialise a list to store accuracy score for each K
for k in neighbors: # looping for each k and finding the accuracy
    # KNN classifier for k nearest neighbours
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    
    # fitting the model
    knn.fit(X_train,y_train)
    
    # predicting the response
    y_pred = knn.predict(X_test)
    
    # capturing accuracy score
    accuracy_scores.append(accuracy_score(y_test,y_pred))

Trying different Regression models for finding the best model¶

  • We can use K-fold CV technique

Importing the libraries¶

In [68]:
from sklearn import model_selection

from sklearn.svm import SVC # Support Vector Classifier

Defining K-fold CV pipeline¶

In [69]:
def k_fold_cv_pipeline():
    # model initialisations
    log_reg_model = LogisticRegression()  # Logistic regression Classifier

    KNN_model = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=optimal_k)  # KNN Classifier

    naive_bayes_model = GaussianNB()  # Gaussian Naive Bayes

    # Support Vector Machine Classifiers with different kernels
    svc_model_linear = SVC(kernel='linear',C=1,gamma=0.1)
    svc_model_rbf = SVC(kernel='rbf',degree=2,C=1,gamma=0.1)
    svc_model_poly  = SVC(kernel='poly',degree=2,C=1,gamma=0.1)

    # NOTE:: We can also manipulate C and gamma values

    # initialising models in key-value tuples
    models = []
    models.append(('LR', log_reg_model))
    models.append(('KNN', KNN_model))
    models.append(('NB', naive_bayes_model))
    if X.shape[0] < 1500: # use SVM only if the records are lesser, because it would be very high computations
        models.append(('SVM-linear', svc_model_linear))
        models.append(('SVM-poly', svc_model_poly))
        models.append(('SVM-rbf', svc_model_rbf))

    # evaluate each model in turn
    results = []
    model_names = []
    for model_name, model in models:
        kfold = model_selection.KFold(n_splits=10, random_state=4,shuffle=True)
        cv_results = model_selection.cross_val_score(model,X,y, cv=kfold, scoring='accuracy')
        results.append(cv_results)
        model_names.append(model_name)
        msg = model_name + ': ' + str(cv_results.mean()) + ' (' + str(cv_results.std()) +')'
        print(msg)

    # boxplot algorithm comparison
    fig = plt.figure()
    fig.suptitle('Algorithm Comparison')
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
    plt.boxplot(results)
    ax.set_xticklabels(model_names)
    plt.show()
In [70]:
k_fold_cv_pipeline() # using the k-fold-pipeline described above

LR: 0.8419354838709676 (0.07277751079147404)
KNN: 0.832258064516129 (0.05913000896717213)
NB: 0.8129032258064516 (0.06579380017539076)
SVM-linear: 0.8419354838709676 (0.061965718426769505)
SVM-poly: 0.8064516129032258 (0.0691858406113781)
SVM-rbf: 0.4806451612903226 (0.054838709677419335)

Conclusions and Observations:¶

  • The above value of K-NN satisfies our cause of classifying diseased and normal people.
  • The model doesn't have very high accuracy.
  • The above factor may be influenced by high imbalance of data points for each target class. Hence, the model is also affected by random_state which may segregate data in a highly imbalanced fashion for differtent states. Hence, affecting the scores of each train_test_split.
  • The above case study can be made better by getting balanced data points for each target class or also by using other classification algorithms like SVC.
  • There is also high computational complexity imnvolved in K-NN.
  • We can also use SMOTE to overcome target imbalance problem.

A campaign that the bank ran in last quarter showed an average single digit conversion rate. Observations:¶

  • As seen from above analysis, there is huge imbalance between the classes in the target variable.
  • This should be fixed by bringing in balanced data for the target classes or there can be some techniques applied before building the model. If we do not treat the data before model building, the model will be more inclined to one of the target class than the other. Some techniques used are:
    • Use metrics like precision, recall, F1-score.
    • Over-sampling tries to balance dataset by increasing the size of rare samples, rather than getting rid of abundant samples using SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-Sampling Technique).
    • Under-sampling balances the dataset by reducing the size of the abundant class.
  • We will use over-sampling and only on train data because:
    • we don't want to loose on data that would be helpful for classification.
    • we shouldn't be over-sampling all the data, because model performance is judged on test or unseen data.
